  <span id="freeText13464273390684354630" style="display:none">Remarkable little (60 pages) book written by former U.S. poet laureate Ted Kooser. He feels that writing this book is the most important work he has ever done and introduces it this way:<br />"From the time I was a little boy I dreamed of one day writing a marvelous book about my mother's family."<br />He has done just that.<br /><br />His family is of Swiss/German heritage and settled in Osterdock and then Guttenberg,Iowa. Family names so different from my own; names like:<br />Clarence, Mabel, Alvah, Dorthea, Harvey and (my favorite) Parthenia.<br /><br />Here are a few gems:<br />"I fasten on every detail, as if it were a button on his coat." <br />(looking at an old photo of a little-known relative)<br />" I have begun to see his hands out at the end of my arms."<br /><br />Reading this leaves me feeling all misty "like the cool colors of summer shadows."<br /><br /><br /></span>
