<div id="review_147686614" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/147686614" />
    <a title="Texx Norman" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4500515-texx-norman"><img alt="Texx Norman" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1483883640p2/4500515.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/147686614?book_show_action=true">Feb 12, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Texx Norman" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Texx Norman" href="/user/show/4500515-texx-norman">Texx Norman</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer147686614" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14937628557586869568">Kooser is my favorite of all my favorite poets, so any time I find anything he has written I read it. This memoir (in prose) was just great. In one passage, about some ancestor of his that died in infancy, he tells about the baby’s headstone. The M.L.M. initials were broken from its base. He thinks someone brought the broken piece of headstone home and planned to return and cement it back into place. That never happened. Then, when the house sold, Kooser’s mother got the MLM stone and kept it wi</span>
  <span id="freeText14937628557586869568" style="display:none">Kooser is my favorite of all my favorite poets, so any time I find anything he has written I read it. This memoir (in prose) was just great. In one passage, about some ancestor of his that died in infancy, he tells about the baby’s headstone. The M.L.M. initials were broken from its base. He thinks someone brought the broken piece of headstone home and planned to return and cement it back into place. That never happened. Then, when the house sold, Kooser’s mother got the MLM stone and kept it with her. Now, the MLM stone, about the size of a brick, is on Kooser’s desk. No one alive knows where baby Millard’s grave is. The poet notices a spot of pain on the baby’s headstone and writes [quote] “The drop is the size of a doorbell, and sometimes I put my finger on it as is I thought it might open a door into the past.” Wonderful sentences like that are found all through this little book. I’m so fortunate to have found it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14937628557586869568" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


